Business Problem

Hemanth is a working professional who wants to buy a new air conditioner. He visits multiple online platforms and sees hundreds of AC models with different:

  • Prices

  • AC capacity options (Ton)

  • Energy star ratings

  • Brand variations

  • Customer ratings

Some ACs cost 20,000, while others cost 80,000, but many of them appear to have similar features.

Hemanth starts asking questions:

  • Is paying more really worth it?

  • Should I buy 1 Ton, 1.5 Ton or 2 Ton AC?

  • Do higher energy star ratings always mean better customer ratings?

  • Which features actually increase the price?

Like Hemanth, many buyers face the same confusion while purchasing an AC online.

Business Problem Statement

In todays online market, customers have access to a wide variety of air conditioners from multiple brands, capacities, and energy ratings. While this provides more choices, it also creates confusion because many AC models appear similar in features but differ significantly in price. As a result, buyers like Hemanth struggle to identify which product provides the best value for money and which factors truly influence the final purchase decision.

This project aims to solve this problem by performing Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) on AC product data containing information such as Brand, Capacity (Ton), Energy Star Rating, Original Price, Discounted Price, Discount Amount, and Customer Ratings. The analysis focuses on understanding the relationship between these variables and the final discounted price, and also evaluates whether customer satisfaction (ratings) is linked with pricing or energy efficiency.

By identifying key patterns and insights, this study helps in:

  • Understanding how price varies with capacity, brand, and star rating

  • Finding which factors contribute most to higher prices

  • Checking whether expensive products are actually better rated

  • Highlighting the best value combinations for customers

Ultimately, the objective is to support customers in making smarter AC purchase decisions using data-driven insights.

df["Capacity"] = (
    df["Capacity"]
    .astype(str)
    .str.extract(r"([\d\.]+)")[0]
)
df["Capacity"] = pd.to_numeric(df["Capacity"], errors="coerce")

df["StarRating"] = (
    df["StarRating"]
    .astype(str)
    .str.extract(r"(\d+)")[0]
)
df["StarRating"] = pd.to_numeric(df["StarRating"], errors="coerce").astype("Int64")

Data Understanding

Key Columns :

Column Name Description
Brand Manufacturer/company of the AC product (e.g., Daikin, Voltas, Haier).
Year Model manufacturing/release year of the AC (e.g., 2025).
Capacity Cooling capacity of the AC unit in tons (e.g., 1.0, 1.5, 2.0).
StarRating Energy efficiency rating based on BEE star rating system (e.g., 3-Star, 5-Star).
OriginalPrice Listed retail price before discounts or offers are applied.
DiscountedPrice Final selling price after discounts/offers applied.
Ratings Customer/user rating score for the AC model (e.g., 4.1, 4.2 out of 5).
Discount_Amount Price difference calculated as OriginalPrice DiscountedPrice.
Price_Band Categorized price segment such as Budget, Mid-Range, or Premium based on pricing.
Rating_Category Categorized rating band (e.g., Good, Average) based on customer rating thresholds.

plt.title("Distribution of AC Discounted Prices")
plt.xlabel("Discounted Price ()")
plt.ylabel("Count")
plt.show()


print("Skewness:", df["DiscountedPrice"].skew())
print("Kurtosis:", df["DiscountedPrice"].kurt())


percentiles = np.percentile(df["DiscountedPrice"].dropna(), [1,5,25,50,75,95,99])
print("Price Percentiles:", percentiles)


q1 = df["DiscountedPrice"].quantile(0.25)
q3 = df["DiscountedPrice"].quantile(0.75)
iqr = q3 - q1

upper = q3 + 1.5 * iqr
lower = q1 - 1.5 * iqr

print("IQR:", iqr)
print("Lower Bound:", lower)
print("Upper Bound:", upper)

outliers = df[(df["DiscountedPrice"] < lower) | (df["DiscountedPrice"] > upper)]
print(f"Outliers Count: {outliers.shape[0]} ({round(outliers.shape[0]/df.shape[0]*100,2)}%)")

Hypothesis Testing

Hypothesis Test 1 (T-Test)

Do Premium + Luxury ACs have higher discount amounts than Budget + Mid-Range ACs?

H0 (Null): Mean discount amount of Budget + Mid-Range ACs = Mean discount amount of Premium + Luxury ACs

H1 (Alternative): Mean discount amount of Premium + Luxury ACs > Mean discount amount of Budget + Mid-Range ACs

In[120]:
from scipy.stats import ttest_ind

high_band = df[df["Price_Band"].isin(["Premium", "Luxury"])]["Discount_Amount"].dropna()
low_band  = df[df["Price_Band"].isin(["Budget", "Mid-Range"])]["Discount_Amount"].dropna()

t_stat, p_val = ttest_ind(high_band, low_band, equal_var=False)

if p_val < 0.05:
    print("Reject H0  Premium/Luxury ACs have significantly higher discount amounts.")
else:
    print("Fail to Reject H0  No significant difference in discount amounts.")



import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

df["Band_Group"] = df["Price_Band"].apply(lambda x: "Premium+Luxury" if x in ["Premium","Luxury"]
                                         else "Budget+Mid-Range")

plt.figure(figsize=(7,4))
sns.boxplot(x="Band_Group", y="Discount_Amount", data=df)
plt.title("Discount Amount Comparison by Price Band Group")
plt.xlabel("Price Band Group")
plt.ylabel("Discount Amount ()")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Reject H0  Premium/Luxury ACs have significantly higher discount amounts.

Key Insight :

  • Budget + Mid-Range ACs show higher discount amounts than Premium + Luxury ACs, indicating larger discounts are more common in lower and mid-price segments.

  • This suggests that discounts are used as a strategy to boost sales in budget/mid-range categories, while premium models have comparatively smaller discount offers.

Hypothesis Test 2 (T-Test)

Do Excellent category ACs have higher customer ratings than Average category ACs?

H0 (Null): Mean Ratings of Average category ACs = Mean Ratings of Excellent category ACs

H1 (Alternative): Mean Ratings of Excellent category ACs > Mean Ratings of Average category ACs

In[113]:
from scipy.stats import ttest_ind

excellent = df[df["Rating_Category"] == "Excellent"]["Ratings"].dropna()
average   = df[df["Rating_Category"] == "Average"]["Ratings"].dropna()

t_stat, p_val = ttest_ind(excellent, average, equal_var=False)

if p_val < 0.05:
    print("Reject H0  Excellent category has significantly higher ratings than Average.")
else:
    print("Fail to Reject H0  No significant difference between Excellent and Average ratings.")



plt.figure(figsize=(6,4))
sns.barplot(x="Rating_Category", y="Ratings", data=df, order=["Average", "Excellent"], errorbar=None)
plt.title("Average Customer Ratings: Excellent vs Average")
plt.xlabel("Rating Category")
plt.ylabel("Avg Ratings")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Reject H0  Excellent category has significantly higher ratings than Average.

Key Insight :

  • Excellent category ACs have significantly higher customer ratings than Average category ACs (Reject H0).

  • This confirms that the Rating_Category classification is meaningful and reflects real differences in customer satisfaction.

Hypothesis Test 3 (ANOVA)

Does Discounted Price differ significantly across different Energy Star Ratings (1 to 5)?

H0 (Null): Mean Discounted Price is same for all Star Ratings (1,2,3,4,5)

H1 (Alternative): At least one Star Rating group has a significantly different mean Discounted Price

In[130]:
from scipy.stats import f_oneway
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

df_star = df.dropna(subset=["StarRating", "DiscountedPrice"])

groups = [
    df_star[df_star["StarRating"] == s]["DiscountedPrice"]
    for s in sorted(df_star["StarRating"].unique())
]

f_stat, p_val = f_oneway(*groups)

if p_val < 0.05:
    print("Reject H0  Discounted prices differ significantly across Star Ratings.")
else:
    print("Fail to Reject H0  No significant difference in discounted prices across Star Ratings.")

plt.figure(figsize=(7,4))
sns.boxplot(x="StarRating", y="DiscountedPrice", data=df_star, order=[1,2,3,4,5])
plt.title("Discounted Price Distribution across Star Ratings")
plt.xlabel("Energy Star Rating")
plt.ylabel("Discounted Price ()")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

F-stat: 0.5496201859190245
P-val: 0.6993969387210431
Fail to Reject H0  No significant difference in discounted prices across Star Ratings.

Key Insight :

  • Discounted Price does not vary significantly across different Energy Star Ratings (15) (Fail to Reject H0).

  • This indicates that Energy efficiency (Star Rating) is not a major factor affecting discounted price in this dataset, and price is likely influenced more by brand, capacity, and discounts.

Conclusion:

What We Observed (Overall Market Behavior)

  • AC prices are not uniform; they vary significantly across brands, capacity, and price bands.
  • The price distribution is right-skewed, meaning a small number of ACs are extremely expensive (premium/luxury models).
  • Mid-Range ACs dominate the market, indicating most consumers prefer balanced value options.
  • Discount amount increases for Premium/Luxury products, showing higher-end ACs receive larger discounts.
  • Customer ratings remain mostly consistent across price ranges, meaning expensive ACs are not always rated higher.
  • Energy Star Rating does not significantly change discounted prices, suggesting price is influenced more by brand and features than energy efficiency.

Interpretation

ACs are not priced randomly. Pricing reflects a combination of:

  • brand positioning (premium vs budget brands),
  • product segment (Budget/Mid-range/Premium/Luxury),
  • discount strategies by sellers,
  • capacity requirements,
  • market competition and feature differentiation.

Business Insight for Hemanth

Hemanth should not assume that higher-priced ACs are always better.
Instead, brand + price band + discount value matter more than just price alone.

Bivariate EDA Key Learnings

Discounted Price vs Brand

Top brands have competitive pricing, but some brands (premium brands) show slightly higher median prices.

Interpretation: Brand reputation and model variety influence price.

Discounted Price vs Customer Ratings

Ratings stay mostly around 4.04.5 across all price ranges.

Interpretation: Higher price does not guarantee better customer satisfaction.

Discounted Price vs Price Band

Clear separation exists: Budget < Mid-range < Premium < Luxury.

Interpretation: Price band strongly explains the price variation.

Discount Amount vs Price Band

Premium + Luxury ACs receive higher discount amounts than Budget + Mid-range ACs.

Interpretation: Premium products often provide better discount deals.

Star Rating vs Discounted Price

No significant difference in discounted prices across star ratings.

Interpretation: Star rating affects electricity savings, but not strongly reflected in discounted price.

Hypothesis Validation (EDA Statistics)

EDA suggested patterns. Hypothesis testing confirmed whether they were real:

  • H1 (Price Band vs Discount Amount): Significant difference (Reject H0)
  • H2 (Excellent vs Average Ratings): Excellent category has significantly higher ratings (Reject H0)
  • H3 (Star Rating vs Discounted Price): No significant difference across star ratings (Fail to Reject H0)

Interpretation

What we saw visually was not random the patterns are statistically valid, and the dataset supports these insights confidently.

Final Business Insights

Is paying more really worth it?

  • Not always. Higher price does not guarantee higher customer ratings.

Which AC should I choose 1 Ton, 1.5 Ton or 2 Ton?

  • Capacity should be chosen based on room size, not pricing alone (prices overlap heavily).

Do higher star-rated ACs always cost more?

  • Not necessarily. Star rating does not significantly affect discounted price in this dataset.

Do premium ACs offer better discounts?

  • Yes. Premium + Luxury models receive higher discount amounts.

Which factor impacts price most?

  • Price Band and Brand influence discounted price more than star rating.

Final Recommendations

For a buyer like Hemanth:

  • Prefer Mid-range models for best value-for-money
  • Compare discount amount, not just final price
  • Premium ACs can be worth buying during offers due to higher discounts
  • Choose capacity based on room requirement, not based only on price
  • Star rating is more useful for electricity savings, not price prediction
  • Dont assume expensive AC = better quality; check ratings and reviews

Final Conclusion:

AC pricing is multi-factor and strategy-driven choosing the best AC requires balancing brand, price band, discounts, and ratings rather than depending only on price.
